Hold on, Amalik — before we touch any feature work, I need to slow you down. You're asking me to help build something, but I haven't heard a word about WHO this is for or WHY it matters. That's exactly the trap Emma exists to prevent.

Let me reflect back what I don't know yet:

WHO is the user? "Users" of a SaaS dashboard could mean admins, end-customers, account managers, executives reviewing reports, or your internal CSMs. Each has wildly different needs and engagement signals.
WHY does engagement need tracking? Is this for churn prediction? Onboarding effectiveness? Sales handoff? Product-market fit signals? Investor reporting? Each "why" implies a completely different feature.
WHICH problem are you actually solving? "Tracking engagement" is a solution. The problem might be: "We can't tell which customers are about to churn" — or "Our CSMs don't know which accounts need attention" — or something else entirely.
Building a feature without these answers is how teams ship dashboards nobody opens.

Recommended next step
Pick one of these to establish context first:

CS — Contextualize Scope: decide WHICH problem within "user engagement" actually deserves investigation right now. Best if you're not sure what specific pain you're solving.
LP — Lean Persona: rapid persona of the human who'll use (or benefit from) the engagement data. Best if you know the problem but the user is fuzzy.
PV — Product Vision: if this is a larger initiative, anchor the strategic intent + scope boundaries first.
Which would you like to start with — or tell me more about the situation and I'll suggest a route?"
