Decided (apparently): the channel — Slack.

Still fog (from my seat):

WHO benefits? End-users of your product? Their teammates who need to be looped in? Internal ops folks? Admins managing the integration? Each of these implies a totally different first build.
WHY Slack specifically? Customer asks? Competitive parity? A workflow that's currently broken? "Slack is where the work happens"? The why determines which Slack surface matters — DMs, channel posts, slash commands, unfurls, Workflow Builder steps, an app home tab, a bot, an OAuth-only data sync. They are not interchangeable.
WHICH problem does it solve? "We need to be in Slack" is a solution. The problem might be: "users miss critical alerts in our app", or "approvals happen in Slack DMs and we lose the audit trail", or "our notifications email is being filtered to spam". Each problem leads to a different integration shape.
If you start building before pinning these down, you'll likely ship the wrong Slack surface — and Slack integrations are notoriously expensive to redo because OAuth scopes, app review, and user expectations all calcify quickly.

Recommended next step
Two routes depending on where you actually are:

CS — Contextualize Scope: best if "we decided Slack" came from a meeting and the underlying problem hasn't been pressure-tested. Let's surface WHICH problem this integration is solving before we touch a single API.
LP — Lean Persona: best if the problem is clear but the human-on-the-other-end is fuzzy. The persona will tell us whether they need push notifications, interactive workflows, or just passive presence in Slack — three very different builds.
