Amalik, I'm going to gently decline to play oracle here. "What should we do?" on an enterprise-vs-SMB call is exactly the kind of question where giving you an answer would be worse than refusing — because the right answer depends entirely on context I don't have, and a confident-sounding wrong answer from me would just give the loudest voice in the room ammunition.

Refusal is a feature here, not a friction.

But I can help you turn the debate into a decision. The reason your PM team is stuck isn't that they're missing an opinion from an outside voice — it's almost certainly that the debate is happening at the wrong level of abstraction. "Enterprise vs. SMB" is a segment question being used as a proxy for things nobody has separated out:

WHO are we actually best at serving today? (Not aspirationally — today, based on retention, NPS, expansion.)
WHY does the segment choice matter this quarter specifically? (Runway? A competitive window? A hire who unlocks one segment? An existing pipeline weighted one way?)
WHICH problem are we choosing between? Because "focus on enterprise" usually decomposes into 3–4 distinct problems (longer sales cycle, security/compliance, multi-seat admin, SSO) and "focus on SMB" decomposes into a different 3–4 (self-serve onboarding, pricing pressure, churn velocity, support load). The teams aren't really debating segments — they're debating which set of problems they want next quarter to be about.
If the PMs are arguing segments without naming the underlying problems, they'll pick a segment, ship features, and discover six months later they optimized for the wrong problems within that segment.

Recommended next step
CS — Contextualize Scope is the right move here. We'll decompose "enterprise vs. SMB" into the actual problem candidates underneath, evaluate which deserves focus, and your PMs walk back into the room with a problem to commit to — not a segment to argue about.
LP — Lean Persona is a good follow-up once the segment narrows: a lean persona for the chosen segment surfaces whether your team's intuition about that segment matches reality.
PV — Product Vision is worth considering if this debate is recurring — meaning your team doesn't have a shared strategic anchor and is re-litigating segment choices every quarter.
Want to run CS on this? I'll need you (or whoever has the most context) in the room to answer some questions — I won't be able to decompose the problem space without input from someone close to the customers and the business."
