I'm working from assumptions, not interviews. Lean personas are best when grounded in real conversations. Treat this draft as a hypothesis to validate — not a fact to build on.
Here's the sketch:

Lean Persona — "Priya, the Stretched PM"
Role + Context
PM at a 50-person Series A/B startup. Owns a product surface (or two). Reports to a Head of Product or directly to the CEO/CTO. No dedicated data team; maybe one data analyst shared across the company.

The Job She's Hiring Analytics For
"Tell me whether what we shipped last sprint moved the needle, and which thing to ship next." Two jobs really — retrospective validation and forward prioritization — and she'd love one tool that does both.

Top Frictions (today)

Data is everywhere and trustworthy nowhere. Mixpanel says one thing, the SQL dashboard says another, and the CEO quotes a Stripe number in standup that contradicts both.
Instrumentation debt. Half the events she needs aren't tracked, and asking eng to add them competes with feature work.
No time to be a data analyst. She can write basic SQL under duress but doesn't want to. She wants answers, not query-builders.
Stakeholders ask "how's it going?" weekly and she cobbles together a slide deck from screenshots every Monday.
What "Good" Looks Like For Her

One place where the core funnel is unambiguously defined and trusted.
Self-serve answers to ~80% of "did X work?" questions without pinging the analyst.
Auto-generated weekly read-out she can paste into Slack/Notion without re-formatting.
What She Will Not Tolerate

A tool that requires a 2-week instrumentation project before it shows value.
"Powerful" interfaces that demand she think like a data engineer.
Pricing that punishes her as the company scales (per-event, per-seat surprise bills).
Anti-Persona (who this is NOT for)

The data analyst at a 500-person company who wants SQL and warehouse access.
The founder doing analytics solo at a 5-person company (too lightweight, no PM workflow).
Decisions This Persona Should Sharpen

Onboarding flow: must show value within the first session, not after instrumentation.
Default views: pre-built funnel + retention + weekly digest, not a blank canvas.
Integrations priority: Slack/Notion output > advanced SQL warehousing.
Caveats worth naming
"Tracks product analytics" is still a wide job. This sketch assumes retrospective + prioritization, but Priya could also be hiring analytics for experimentation, user-segment discovery, or exec reporting — different personas would emerge for each.
50-person is a transition zone. Below 30 the PM often is the founder; above 75 there's usually a data team. Worth confirming whether your real Priya is closer to 30 or to 75 — the answer changes the friction list.
